{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1236"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0,0.63,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37011"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"702"},{"type":"tags","id":"1847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with acute choking. He was having dinner at a busy restaurant when he suddenly started choking on a piece of food. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, and SpO2 88% on room air. He is conscious and responsive but gasping for air, unable to dislodge the piece of food. He is coughing forcefully but ineffectively.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heimlich manoeuvre","CPR","Back blows and chest thrusts","Encourage coughing","Tracheostomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of severe airway obstruction due to choking on a piece of food. The most appropriate initial response in this situation is to perform \u003Cstrong\u003Eback blows and chest thrusts\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach is recommended by the Australian Resuscitation Council guidelines for responsive patients with severe airway obstruction. Back blows and chest thrusts generate sufficient pressure to attempt to relieve the airway obstruction while being safer than other manoeuvres. The technique involves delivering up to five back blows, followed by chest thrusts if the obstruction persists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EHeimlich manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves abdominal thrusts, is not recommended in Australia due to the risk of serious complications. These can include injury to the abdominal aorta, gastric rupture, rib fracture, and pneumomediastinum. While it may be effective in dislodging foreign bodies, the potential risks outweigh the benefits when safer alternatives are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECPR\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario as the patient is still conscious and responsive. CPR would only be initiated if the patient becomes unresponsive during the choking episode or while receiving treatment. It\u0027s crucial to continually reassess the patient\u0027s level of consciousness and begin CPR if they lose consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncouraging coughing\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for mild airway obstruction where the initial cough is effective in attempting to dislodge the foreign body. However, in this case, the patient\u0027s coughing is described as forceful but ineffective, and he is showing signs of severe respiratory distress. Therefore, encouraging coughing alone would not be sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etracheostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first step in this scenario. While an emergent tracheostomy can be indicated for acute upper airway obstruction where endotracheal intubation has failed or is likely to be difficult, it is an invasive procedure that should only be considered after less invasive methods have been attempted and failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the priority in managing a conscious patient with severe airway obstruction due to choking is to attempt to dislodge the foreign body using back blows and chest thrusts. If these manoeuvres are unsuccessful and the patient becomes unresponsive, then CPR should be initiated, and more invasive airway management techniques may need to be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Back blows and chest thrusts are the recommended initial manoeuvres for responsive patients with severe airway obstruction.","The Heimlich manoeuvre is not recommended in Australia due to the risk of serious complications.","CPR is indicated only if the patient becomes unresponsive during a choking episode."],"references":["ANZCOR foreign body airway obstruction (choking) flowchart. In: Australian Resuscitation Council [online]. 2016. Available at: https://learning.learnprn.com/files/uploads/lp-bls/slide43.pdf","The Heimlich Manoeuvre. In: Australia Wide First Aid [online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.australiawidefirstaid.com.au/resources/the-heimlich-manoeuvre","Ebrahimi M, Mirhaghi A. Heimlich maneuver complications: A systematic review. Eurasian Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2019;18(3):157\u201365. Available at: https://jag.journalagent.com/z4/vi.asp?pdir=atuder\u0026plng=eng\u0026un=EAJEM-21033"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37011"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T12:03:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T12:04:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic